WEBVTT

00:00.668 --> 00:03.504
[ Drumming ]

00:03.537 --> 00:06.607
[ Singing in Patois ]

00:26.694 --> 00:28.496
PAGE: We've arrived in Jamaica

00:28.529 --> 00:31.199
during the highest
of Rastafari holidays --

00:31.232 --> 00:35.336
the birth of Haile Selassie,
former emperor of Ethiopia,

00:35.369 --> 00:38.706
and, to some Rastafari,
the Messiah.

00:50.284 --> 00:53.254
The Rastafari movement was born
out of Jamaica's struggle

00:53.287 --> 00:55.756
to free itself
of the cultural suppression

00:55.789 --> 00:59.059
and slavery imposed
by European imperialism.

01:07.435 --> 01:09.470
A main pillar of its ideology

01:09.503 --> 01:14.575
is the acceptance of all people,
regardless of creed or color.

01:14.608 --> 01:18.146
So this seems a natural starting
point for our exploration

01:18.179 --> 01:20.781
of queer culture and acceptance
in Jamaica,

01:20.814 --> 01:24.485
to hang out with
the preachers of "one love."

01:24.518 --> 01:25.519
Jah!

01:25.553 --> 01:28.456
ALL: Rastafari!

01:28.489 --> 01:33.161
**

01:33.194 --> 01:35.463
* Did you see them?

01:35.496 --> 01:39.167
* Oh, did you see them?

01:39.200 --> 01:42.403
* They're just walking around,
yeah *

01:44.905 --> 01:46.407
DANIEL:
Is that the bar?

01:46.440 --> 01:47.875
MAN: Yeah.

01:47.908 --> 01:49.543
That's like "Waterworld."

01:49.577 --> 01:51.479
[ Laughs ]

01:51.512 --> 01:54.548
PAGE: Jamaica attracts visitors
from all over the world...

01:54.582 --> 01:57.751
-Thank you.
-...with its reggae anthems
of universal love

01:57.785 --> 02:00.588
and its motto,
"Out of many, one people."

02:00.621 --> 02:02.823
Oh, there's crabs everywhere.
Look at that little guy.

02:02.856 --> 02:04.425
DANIEL: Hey, man.
Whoo-hoo.

02:04.458 --> 02:06.894
But in 2006,
Time magazine argued

02:06.927 --> 02:09.730
Jamaica may be the most
homophobic place on Earth.

02:09.763 --> 02:14.735
And nearly a decade later,
half of all LGBTQ surveyed

02:14.768 --> 02:17.205
still report being
victims of violence,

02:17.238 --> 02:20.341
according
to the Human Rights Watch.

02:20.374 --> 02:22.376
Ian and I
are visiting the country

02:22.410 --> 02:24.378
at what could be
a turning point,

02:24.412 --> 02:29.850
as Jamaica holds its very first
public Pride celebration ever.

02:29.883 --> 02:32.686
We hope to see
what real change looks like

02:32.720 --> 02:36.724
at this pivotal moment for
the Jamaican LGBTQ community.

02:36.757 --> 02:39.293
**

02:43.364 --> 02:45.333
The Rastafari community

02:45.366 --> 02:48.569
makes up less than 5%
of the Jamaican population,

02:48.602 --> 02:50.771
but its influence
is significant,

02:50.804 --> 02:52.306
both here and abroad.

02:52.340 --> 02:54.208
We're meeting an elder to get

02:54.242 --> 02:58.246
the Rastafarian perspective
on queer culture in Jamaica.

02:58.279 --> 02:59.880
-Blessings.
-I'm Ellen.

02:59.913 --> 03:02.483
"Helen" with an "H"
or "Ellen" with an "E?"

03:02.516 --> 03:04.652
-"Ellen" with an "E."
-"Ellen" with an "E."

03:04.685 --> 03:06.287
-Yeah, that's it. Yeah.
-[ Laughs ]

03:06.320 --> 03:08.422
-I'm Ian.
-"Ian," with an "I."

03:08.456 --> 03:09.623
-You got it.
[ Laughter ]

03:09.657 --> 03:10.924
You nailed it.

03:10.958 --> 03:14.362
So, can you explain
what Rastafari is?

03:14.395 --> 03:18.832
Well, Rastafari, we are
the Children of His Majesty.

03:18.866 --> 03:21.802
And it was out
of the legacy of slavery.

03:21.835 --> 03:22.903
Right.

03:22.936 --> 03:24.972
We said,
"We are no slaves.

03:25.005 --> 03:27.975
We were the first
Children of the Most High."

03:28.008 --> 03:33.013
Within our liberty, we look
at the Christian doctrine

03:33.046 --> 03:35.816
as they put it to us
through the Bible.

03:35.849 --> 03:39.019
And when we decide for the
Bible, we realized that a lot

03:39.052 --> 03:42.690
of the things are not correct
as they put it in the Bible.

03:42.723 --> 03:47.295
So we have adopted
different Bible texts,

03:47.328 --> 03:49.630
and we have gone even beyond
even the Bible texts.

03:49.663 --> 03:53.801
We have adapted what we call
an Ital lifestyle.

03:53.834 --> 03:58.706
So we try to eat
as close to natural as possible.

03:58.739 --> 04:01.642
And we try to live
a certain life.

04:01.675 --> 04:05.546
And this is why we say
the color of a man's skin

04:05.579 --> 04:08.949
is of no more significance
as the color of his eyes.

04:08.982 --> 04:10.418
Mm.

04:10.451 --> 04:12.786
Because it sounds
like such a beautiful,

04:12.820 --> 04:14.688
very, very peaceful
religion

04:14.722 --> 04:17.758
that stemmed out
of ultimately ending oppression,

04:17.791 --> 04:20.628
I'm curious about the views
towards homosexuality

04:20.661 --> 04:22.863
and what the perspective is
in your culture.

04:22.896 --> 04:25.733
Homosexuality,
we don't believe in,

04:25.766 --> 04:29.370
because homosexuality means
that you're not pro-life.

04:29.403 --> 04:33.307
If we were created
a certain way,

04:33.341 --> 04:36.910
to reproduce,
to continue life,

04:36.944 --> 04:38.746
then that is the way
it should be.

04:38.779 --> 04:41.382
So, what do you think
a gay person is, then?

04:41.415 --> 04:43.917
In my youth days,
we used to call homosexuals

04:43.951 --> 04:46.053
faggot or batty boy.

04:46.086 --> 04:49.590
Batty boys, we used to chase
them and beat them.

04:49.623 --> 04:51.925
Mash them.

04:51.959 --> 04:53.894
Come forward to our way,

04:53.927 --> 04:56.797
and understand that there's
a problem up here.

04:56.830 --> 04:59.700
-Mm-hmm.
-So it's all right.

04:59.733 --> 05:04.605
You're human.
But you have a disorder.

05:04.638 --> 05:06.907
It's hard to hear
from a religion

05:06.940 --> 05:09.042
that really,
the core of it,

05:09.076 --> 05:10.878
as a lot of religions are,

05:10.911 --> 05:14.582
the objective is very
well-intentioned and beautiful,

05:14.615 --> 05:16.384
and then, unfortunately,

05:16.417 --> 05:19.820
all this human beings managed
to do all this weird stuff.

05:19.853 --> 05:23.491
PAGE: One man certainly can't
speak for a whole community,

05:23.524 --> 05:25.826
but do his views
come from his faith,

05:25.859 --> 05:27.428
or are they a byproduct

05:27.461 --> 05:30.498
of a cultural intolerance
for homosexuality?

05:30.531 --> 05:34.702
A recent survey showed
that over 80% of Jamaicans

05:34.735 --> 05:37.571
believe
that homosexuality is immoral.

05:37.605 --> 05:42.676
And in 2010, 1/3 of all people
successfully granted asylum

05:42.710 --> 05:45.479
on the basis of homophobia
through immigration equality

05:45.513 --> 05:47.080
were Jamaican.

05:47.114 --> 05:50.150
Those who don't leave can be
faced with acts of violence,

05:50.183 --> 05:53.787
which have made headlines
around the world.

05:53.821 --> 05:58.025
But we understand that the
reality must be way more complex

05:58.058 --> 06:00.494
than what the media
would have us believe.

06:00.528 --> 06:03.731
Ian and I want to hang out
with a group of young Jamaicans

06:03.764 --> 06:05.933
to get their perspective.

06:05.966 --> 06:08.836
[ Indistinct conversations ]

06:08.869 --> 06:10.170
Hey.

06:10.203 --> 06:12.172
Hi, Ellen.
Hi, Ian.

06:12.205 --> 06:15.609
PAGE:
We are spending the afternoon
with Leighton Mullings,

06:15.643 --> 06:19.680
the director of a travel agency
that caters to queer tourists.

06:19.713 --> 06:20.981
So, for the most part, like,

06:21.014 --> 06:22.916
if I was to visit
with my girlfriend

06:22.950 --> 06:25.586
and wanted to kiss her
in a public area or something,

06:25.619 --> 06:28.055
like, is that something
that's possible, or...

06:28.088 --> 06:29.823
It really does depend
on the level

06:29.857 --> 06:31.459
at which you enter
the space.

06:31.492 --> 06:32.860
What do you mean
by "level"?

06:32.893 --> 06:34.828
Like, this society
is structured on classism.

06:34.862 --> 06:36.597
-Mm-hmm.
-Full stop.

06:36.630 --> 06:39.500
So, if you're in the, you know,
richer LGBT community,

06:39.533 --> 06:42.069
you have a much more enjoyable
life than if you were...

06:42.102 --> 06:44.004
-Yeah, you have more freedom.
-Yeah.

06:44.037 --> 06:45.773
You're afforded
that luxury.

06:45.806 --> 06:48.709
You know, the courtesies and
not being attacked, et cetera,

06:48.742 --> 06:50.711
based on what you communicate
to them

06:50.744 --> 06:52.813
that your socioeconomic
status may be.

06:52.846 --> 06:56.083
-Sure.
-You're not only able to afford
a good life here...

06:56.116 --> 06:58.786
-Mm-hmm.
-...you're also able to escape,
you know,

06:58.819 --> 07:01.121
to travel and have
the vacation experiences

07:01.154 --> 07:04.858
that you're having overseas
in another country.
-Sure. Mm-hmm.

07:04.892 --> 07:08.161
So, before coming to Jamaica,
our research and everything

07:08.195 --> 07:11.865
is that it's really difficult
to be gay in Jamaica.

07:11.899 --> 07:14.902
A lot of the sentiment, I feel,
that, you know,

07:14.935 --> 07:16.870
in terms
of the homophobia,

07:16.904 --> 07:19.139
is the result
of heavy patriarchy.

07:19.172 --> 07:22.042
It's that heavy, heavy hand
that colonialism dealt us.

07:22.075 --> 07:23.977
You know,
we're still hemorrhaging

07:24.011 --> 07:25.879
from that experience,
I believe.

07:25.913 --> 07:27.948
But at the same time, though,
the narrative

07:27.981 --> 07:30.518
has to be balanced,
coming out of here.
-Mm-hmm.

07:30.551 --> 07:34.722
I'm not negating the horror
stories that you guys hear.

07:34.755 --> 07:36.223
But it's more complex,

07:36.256 --> 07:39.660
and there's more beneath
the surface than does appear.

07:39.693 --> 07:42.696
The point is, in that kind
of culture and society,

07:42.730 --> 07:44.932
that it certainly must be
dangerous

07:44.965 --> 07:46.834
to be
an openly gay person.

07:46.867 --> 07:50.571
-It always is, yeah.
-Right.

07:50.604 --> 07:53.807
PAGE: Considering there is not
one publicly open gay bar

07:53.841 --> 07:55.208
in the entire country,

07:55.242 --> 07:58.111
Bloom offers a safe space
for the gay traveler,

07:58.145 --> 08:00.881
and throws some of the most
sexually open parties

08:00.914 --> 08:02.583
in all of Jamaica.

08:02.616 --> 08:06.053
And while Ian and I are out,
we aren't in the open,

08:06.086 --> 08:11.024
as we hang out on this beautiful
but very secluded beach.

08:11.058 --> 08:12.793
**

08:12.826 --> 08:14.762
DANIEL: Can you share
your personal experience

08:14.795 --> 08:17.631
of what it's like to be gay
in Jamaica?

08:17.665 --> 08:19.600
-Quite tragic. Sad.
-Yeah.

08:19.633 --> 08:21.535
Puts me
in a lonely place.

08:21.569 --> 08:24.538
So, what is a day like
in your life in Jamaica, then?

08:24.572 --> 08:27.675
There is a feeling that you get
every day when you wake up.

08:27.708 --> 08:29.677
Something might happen.
Hopefully, nothing does.

08:29.710 --> 08:31.044
But...

08:31.078 --> 08:33.814
Like, something specific
has happened to you?

08:33.847 --> 08:36.850
Um, I was riding home
from work one day.

08:36.884 --> 08:39.820
I went by the football park,
and there was this crowd.

08:39.853 --> 08:42.656
I just felt something inside
of me say, you know, like,

08:42.690 --> 08:45.292
"Get -- Get -- Get ready.
Get wary." You know, "Be wary."

08:45.325 --> 08:47.961
And I heard a girl shout,
"Make way for the batty boy!

08:47.995 --> 08:49.597
Make way
for the batty boy!"

08:49.630 --> 08:52.032
And I heard a clink
and another clank.

08:52.065 --> 08:53.601
People were throwing rocks
at me.

08:53.634 --> 08:55.569
And "batty boy,"
is that what she said?

08:55.603 --> 08:57.871
Is that -- That's a term?
-Yeah, they said,
"Make way for the --"

08:57.905 --> 08:59.206
-Yeah.
-It's a homophobic slur

08:59.239 --> 09:00.908
for -- for -- for gay people
in this country.

09:00.941 --> 09:04.044
I made my report.
Nothing happened.

09:04.077 --> 09:07.014
Getting justice doesn't work
so well in this country

09:07.047 --> 09:08.882
if you're a homosexual...

09:08.916 --> 09:11.785
-Yeah.
-...because they don't care.

09:11.819 --> 09:14.588
DANIEL:
We heard that Jamaica is having
its first Gay Pride parade.

09:14.622 --> 09:15.923
Do you know anything
about that?

09:15.956 --> 09:17.157
This is
how I feel about it.

09:17.190 --> 09:19.993
People are not ready
for that.

09:20.027 --> 09:22.229
Right. You think there will be
retaliation toward that?

09:22.262 --> 09:24.932
There are many people
who are accepting,

09:24.965 --> 09:27.868
but there is a group of people
who are very --

09:27.901 --> 09:30.337
They can retaliate
like this.

09:30.370 --> 09:33.240
And they're not afraid
to retaliate.

09:35.075 --> 09:38.846
The story we just heard
seems to be in line with...

09:38.879 --> 09:42.215
pretty much everything
I was kind of expecting to hear.

09:42.249 --> 09:45.318
DANIEL: All we can do is, like,
hear that in the news media,

09:45.352 --> 09:47.120
come here
and talk to people.

09:47.154 --> 09:49.823
So we're still at the beginning
of the trip, and we don't --

09:49.857 --> 09:53.393
-Absolutely.
-I'm still feeling
like I don't know.

09:58.899 --> 10:00.333
PAGE:
It's late here in Jamaica,

10:00.367 --> 10:03.170
but for some, the night
is just getting started.

10:03.203 --> 10:05.873
If you are young
and not a tourist,

10:05.906 --> 10:08.341
chances are you're headed
to a dancehall night.

10:08.375 --> 10:10.243
[ Air horn blowing ]

10:10.277 --> 10:12.145
[ Reggae music playing ]

10:12.179 --> 10:14.882
The dancehall movement
emerged in the 1970s,

10:14.915 --> 10:18.786
and like the idealistic messages
associated with reggae,

10:18.819 --> 10:21.989
dancehall is an unfiltered
expression of life

10:22.022 --> 10:23.724
for many Jamaicans.

10:23.757 --> 10:25.425
-[ Shouting indistinctly ]
-But more than just music,

10:25.458 --> 10:28.295
dancehall is
a highly influential culture.

10:28.328 --> 10:31.732
At its most extreme,
it projects raw sexuality,

10:31.765 --> 10:35.836
masculinity,
and, infamously, homophobia.

10:35.869 --> 10:37.204
**

10:37.237 --> 10:39.807
This is demonstrated
most prominently

10:39.840 --> 10:41.408
in some of dancehall's
biggest hits

10:41.441 --> 10:44.011
of the '90s and early 2000s...

10:44.044 --> 10:46.814
**

10:46.847 --> 10:49.983
...with lyrics translated
to mean, "We don't like gay men.

10:50.017 --> 10:51.018
They have to die."

10:51.051 --> 10:52.920
**

10:52.953 --> 10:55.188
"Shoot a gay man in the head."

10:55.222 --> 10:56.790
**

10:56.824 --> 10:59.026
Or "Hang a lesbian
with a long rope."

10:59.059 --> 11:00.293
[ Indistinct shouting ]

11:00.327 --> 11:03.130
Some have labeled it
"murder music."

11:03.163 --> 11:04.965
You're batty boys!
We don't like you!

11:04.998 --> 11:08.135
Condemnation and protests
from activists abroad

11:08.168 --> 11:11.404
has helped push back
against some of these messages.

11:11.438 --> 11:15.943
And in 2012, Beenie Man,
known as the King of Dancehall,

11:15.976 --> 11:18.445
was forced to publicly address
certain songs

11:18.478 --> 11:20.213
from earlier in his career.

11:20.247 --> 11:22.349
I have nothing against no one.

11:22.382 --> 11:25.185
I respect
each and every human being.

11:25.218 --> 11:27.387
Regardless of sexual preference,

11:27.420 --> 11:30.090
including
gay and lesbian people.

11:30.123 --> 11:33.794
Do not fight against me for some
song that I sing 20 years ago.

11:33.827 --> 11:35.462
PAGE:
We're meeting with Beenie Man

11:35.495 --> 11:37.430
to learn more
about dancehall culture

11:37.464 --> 11:41.735
and its relationship
to the LGBTQ community.

11:41.769 --> 11:43.503
-Hey, guys.
-Hi.

11:43.536 --> 11:44.805
-Hey.
-Hey.

11:44.838 --> 11:45.973
-How's it going?
-You good?

11:46.006 --> 11:48.341
Hey, I'm Ian.
-Hey, I'm Ellen.

11:48.375 --> 11:50.143
PAGE:
Nice to meet you.

11:50.177 --> 11:53.246
Obviously, so many people
are very familiar with reggae.

11:53.280 --> 11:56.249
I think they're less familiar
with dancehall.

12:11.298 --> 12:13.901
Did the themes of the music
change from, like,

12:13.934 --> 12:15.202
the -- the message

12:15.235 --> 12:18.138
of, like, compassion
and social protest and...

12:22.109 --> 12:23.777
Some of the issues
about it,

12:23.811 --> 12:26.013
being able to be played
around the world, though,

12:26.046 --> 12:27.981
have had to do with a lot
of the LGBT,

12:28.015 --> 12:31.151
sort of anti-gay lyrics.
-Yeah, but. Yeah...

12:32.152 --> 12:33.854
Right.

13:05.886 --> 13:08.255
Right. Right. Right.

13:11.959 --> 13:13.460
Well, because
you have to understand

13:13.493 --> 13:14.995
that dancehall has
extreme --

13:15.028 --> 13:17.397
Well, it has
very extreme influence.

13:17.430 --> 13:20.901
No, it's - it's --
it's influential.

13:20.934 --> 13:22.970
No, I'm not -- you know --
Yeah?

13:29.309 --> 13:31.444
No, it's actually not judgment,
I swear to you.

13:31.478 --> 13:33.480
It's about -- No, no, no.
It's not judgment.

13:33.513 --> 13:35.382
It's about --
We're gay, right?

13:35.415 --> 13:38.085
So when we come to a place
and we meet gay people

13:38.118 --> 13:40.253
and they're suffering greatly.
-Mm-hmm.

13:40.287 --> 13:42.856
They're suffering violence,
depression, shame.

13:42.890 --> 13:44.391
That's all.

13:54.601 --> 13:58.105
I know, but we heard lots
of stories that, you know...

13:58.138 --> 13:59.973
I don't think --
That's -- That's fine.

14:00.007 --> 14:02.042
I don't think it's a lie,
but --

14:07.915 --> 14:09.883
It seems to be,
you know, really hard

14:09.917 --> 14:12.419
for people who are gay
or lesbian here.

14:12.452 --> 14:14.221
Really hard.

14:14.254 --> 14:17.457
And would you like to see that,
you know, change for people?

14:21.594 --> 14:24.297
-Right.
-You'd...

14:24.331 --> 14:27.067
You'd love her, right?
Yeah.

14:27.100 --> 14:31.104
But wouldn't you hope that she
could -- could love someone,

14:31.138 --> 14:35.508
hold their hand walking
down the street, marry them.

14:35.542 --> 14:37.410
Yeah.

14:37.444 --> 14:40.113
And I understand that,
as a protective father,

14:40.147 --> 14:42.315
to not -- to not want
your daughter to be hurt.

14:42.349 --> 14:45.152
I'm saying, wouldn't you
just wish that for her,

14:45.185 --> 14:47.187
for her life?

14:47.220 --> 14:50.390
I know.
It's hypothetical.

14:50.423 --> 14:52.225
Mm-hmm.

14:56.096 --> 14:57.998
Right.

15:00.333 --> 15:01.468
Mm-hmm.

15:07.407 --> 15:08.641
Right.

15:08.675 --> 15:10.643
Two women together
is very hot to me.

15:10.677 --> 15:12.980
-[ Sighs ]
-Yeah. [ Chuckles ]

15:15.348 --> 15:18.118
Yeah. There. We agree there.
Yeah. Cool.

15:18.151 --> 15:20.087
Yeah.
[ Laughter ]

15:23.390 --> 15:25.725
As a response
to the media backlash,

15:25.758 --> 15:28.395
perhaps
for purely commercial reasons,

15:28.428 --> 15:32.032
or because some may actually
have become more accepting,

15:32.065 --> 15:35.002
in the past few years,
most major dancehall artists

15:35.035 --> 15:37.170
have stopped writing
anti-gay lyrics.

15:37.204 --> 15:39.106
**

15:39.139 --> 15:42.342
The one thing possibly more
influential than the music here

15:42.375 --> 15:44.244
is religion.

15:44.277 --> 15:48.448
First brought to the island by
the Spanish over 500 years ago,

15:48.481 --> 15:51.618
the power of religion
reaches far here.

15:51.651 --> 15:53.253
It's even been claimed

15:53.286 --> 15:55.755
that Jamaica has more churches
per square mile

15:55.788 --> 15:58.658
than any other country
in the world.

15:58.691 --> 16:01.194
So we want to speak
with Bishop Alvin Bailey

16:01.228 --> 16:03.496
of the Portmore Holiness
Christian Church

16:03.530 --> 16:05.098
to help us understand

16:05.132 --> 16:08.735
the religion's perspective
on being queer.

16:08.768 --> 16:11.504
DANIEL: So, how does the Church
feel about homosexuality?

16:11.538 --> 16:14.141
All Christian denominations
in Jamaica

16:14.174 --> 16:17.077
not feel the Bible teaches
that homosexuality,

16:17.110 --> 16:19.479
the practice of homosexuality,
is sin.

16:19.512 --> 16:23.383
But the homosexual person
is God's divine creation,

16:23.416 --> 16:26.419
like every one of us, to be
redeemed by the power of God,

16:26.453 --> 16:28.055
and we believe
that God can do that.

16:28.088 --> 16:29.489
Is your belief
that people

16:29.522 --> 16:32.659
who are -- who -- who are gay
aren't born gay?

16:32.692 --> 16:35.062
We have no evidence
in Scripture to suggest

16:35.095 --> 16:37.197
that God created any person
a homosexual,

16:37.230 --> 16:38.531
in pretty much the same way

16:38.565 --> 16:40.400
that He has never created anyone
an adulterer.

16:40.433 --> 16:42.335
Have you -- Do you know some
other practice,

16:42.369 --> 16:43.736
for example,
of some of the gays?

16:43.770 --> 16:46.039
Do you know about things
like fisting and slurching

16:46.073 --> 16:48.041
and those kinds of behaviors
that are not human,

16:48.075 --> 16:50.110
that are not normal
for most persons?

16:50.143 --> 16:51.811
-I would actually say
there are straight people...
-Straight people.

16:51.844 --> 16:53.580
...that, also,
for sure fist,

16:53.613 --> 16:55.182
and I would say there's
a lot of gay people who don't.

16:55.215 --> 16:56.783
What was the other term
that you said?

16:56.816 --> 16:58.718
I'm sorry, you said something
after fisting.

16:58.751 --> 17:00.387
I've never heard that word
before.

17:00.420 --> 17:01.621
-Slurching.
-Slurching?

17:01.654 --> 17:03.356
-Yeah, what's slurching?
-What is that?

17:03.390 --> 17:06.259
Slurching is -- is -- is -- is
the discharging in the anus

17:06.293 --> 17:08.795
and then suck it from the anus
of the individual.

17:08.828 --> 17:11.298
-Mm.
-Like, oh, with your mouth?

17:11.331 --> 17:14.667
Yes. We are not used to that
kind of practices for two men.

17:14.701 --> 17:17.704
Even the whole business
of French kissing in public

17:17.737 --> 17:20.307
might be okay
for a heterosexual couple.

17:20.340 --> 17:22.775
In our society,
we are not totally used to

17:22.809 --> 17:25.078
that kind of thing,
maybe as yet.

17:25.112 --> 17:27.414
So, then do you think at some
point the LGBT community

17:27.447 --> 17:29.816
could potentially align
with your church?

17:29.849 --> 17:32.119
It is never likely
that any church

17:32.152 --> 17:34.721
is going to be aligned
to any homosexual group

17:34.754 --> 17:38.391
to the point
where we become synchronized.

17:38.425 --> 17:40.560
**

17:44.897 --> 17:47.100
PAGE: Jamaica
may have gained independence

17:47.134 --> 17:51.271
from the British in 1962,
but remnants of colonialism

17:51.304 --> 17:55.142
still significantly impact
the queer community.

17:55.175 --> 17:59.779
Most notably, the so-called
"buggery law" is still in place.

17:59.812 --> 18:03.583
It's a set of articles
which deems sodomy illegal,

18:03.616 --> 18:04.851
carrying a punishment

18:04.884 --> 18:07.654
of 10 years' hard labor
or imprisonment.

18:07.687 --> 18:11.324
To this day, the law
has not been overturned,

18:11.358 --> 18:14.394
despite the best efforts
of human rights groups

18:14.427 --> 18:17.397
and an appeal
by the United Nations.

18:17.430 --> 18:19.732
We are meeting with Jamaica's
Minister of Justice,

18:19.766 --> 18:22.135
Mark Golding, to find out more.

18:22.169 --> 18:24.337
We're just wondering,
from your perspective,

18:24.371 --> 18:25.772
how you see the buggery law,

18:25.805 --> 18:27.440
because it's a symbol
that there is some sort

18:27.474 --> 18:31.378
of government-sanctioned form
of discrimination.

18:31.411 --> 18:35.515
It's a hot potato
to attempt to touch it.

18:35.548 --> 18:38.885
And the feeling is that
it would be counterproductive

18:38.918 --> 18:40.687
to have a debate like that

18:40.720 --> 18:43.690
if the result would not be
to move forward...

18:43.723 --> 18:45.358
Sure.
-...you know?

18:45.392 --> 18:48.461
It would be sort of like 2016,
a reaffirmation

18:48.495 --> 18:52.432
of an 1861, I think it is,
Victorian statute.

18:52.465 --> 18:56.536
Do you think that the buggery
law will ever be repealed?

18:56.569 --> 18:57.804
I do.

18:57.837 --> 18:59.606
-Yeah?
-I do think it will be.

18:59.639 --> 19:03.210
One thing I would say is I
believe people need to respect

19:03.243 --> 19:06.646
countries' and societies'
feelings on these issues.

19:06.679 --> 19:11.884
You know, America, for example,
only recently got to the point

19:11.918 --> 19:15.522
where gay marriage has been held
by their highest court.

19:15.555 --> 19:17.657
They have evolved
at their own pace.

19:17.690 --> 19:21.561
So countries like ours,
there's a resistance to that.

19:21.594 --> 19:24.331
We don't really see it
as the role of other countries

19:24.364 --> 19:26.399
to tell us
at what pace we must evolve.

19:26.433 --> 19:29.436
Is there any controversy
against the Pride events

19:29.469 --> 19:33.340
that are happening, and what
do you think will happen when...

19:33.373 --> 19:36.776
Um, it's the first time
Jamaica is having this done.

19:36.809 --> 19:39.646
I'm a little nervous,
I must tell you.

19:39.679 --> 19:42.749
But I would like it
to go through smoothly,

19:42.782 --> 19:44.384
without incident.

19:44.417 --> 19:47.420
I'm cautiously optimistic
that it will go quietly.

19:47.454 --> 19:48.921
**

19:48.955 --> 19:50.490
PAGE: I can understand

19:50.523 --> 19:52.992
that a country can only change
at its own pace,

19:53.025 --> 19:55.762
but until then,
it isn't just the buggery law.

19:55.795 --> 19:58.531
It's the complete absence
of legal protection

19:58.565 --> 20:00.367
for queer citizens

20:00.400 --> 20:04.003
that renders them invisible
in the eyes of the government.

20:04.036 --> 20:09.309
It's been estimated that 32,000
Jamaicans are living with HIV

20:09.342 --> 20:13.012
and as many as half of them
are unaware of their status.

20:13.045 --> 20:15.548
And of those
who know they've been infected,

20:15.582 --> 20:19.319
the power of the church, the
laws that criminalize sex acts,

20:19.352 --> 20:20.853
and the threat of violence

20:20.887 --> 20:23.790
is often enough to keep them
from seeking treatment.

20:23.823 --> 20:25.658
To learn more about this issue,

20:25.692 --> 20:27.860
we are visiting
Kandasi Levermore

20:27.894 --> 20:31.931
of the pioneering organization
Jamaica AIDS Support for Life.

20:31.964 --> 20:37.304
Our focus is bringing the
information for HIV to everyone,

20:37.337 --> 20:42.375
from HIV prevention, treatment,
care, and support services.

20:42.409 --> 20:46.546
But any type of communication
around understanding

20:46.579 --> 20:49.716
homosexuality
and sexual orientation

20:49.749 --> 20:53.986
is seen as pro-gay and
putting forward a gay agenda.

20:54.020 --> 20:55.688
And the challenge
that we have

20:55.722 --> 20:58.958
is that we cannot work
with young people.

20:58.991 --> 21:00.627
I would have to report

21:00.660 --> 21:03.696
when someone under the age of 18
comes to my clinic.

21:03.730 --> 21:05.365
-Mm.
-So there's a disparity.

21:05.398 --> 21:07.634
Because age of consent
is 16, but the age

21:07.667 --> 21:10.570
at which they can access
services on their own is 18.

21:10.603 --> 21:12.038
They can come.

21:12.071 --> 21:13.940
It's just that they have to come
with their parents.

21:13.973 --> 21:15.742
-Oh, wow.
-Now, what that does,

21:15.775 --> 21:17.810
it -- it pushes people away
from service.

21:17.844 --> 21:19.312
They don't
want to come out.

21:19.346 --> 21:21.080
So you're are young
and having sex.

21:21.113 --> 21:23.082
That alone is a challenge.
-Mm-hmm.

21:23.115 --> 21:26.519
But then you're having sex
with same sex, whoa,

21:26.553 --> 21:28.821
it's just very difficult
for them.

21:28.855 --> 21:30.823
And I imagine, even,
just the thought

21:30.857 --> 21:33.960
of coming to get treatment,
that's a risk unto itself.
-Yeah.

21:33.993 --> 21:35.895
So, we call it
the double stigma.

21:35.928 --> 21:37.664
We call it a catch-22.

21:37.697 --> 21:40.600
What is so horrific
is potentially a young man here

21:40.633 --> 21:43.336
would tell
his, you know, parents

21:43.370 --> 21:45.372
and be kicked out
of the house.

21:45.405 --> 21:46.873
In some instances,

21:46.906 --> 21:49.809
it's not just the parents
that force gay people to leave.

21:49.842 --> 21:51.511
It's the community.
-Mm.

21:51.544 --> 21:53.746
The stares, the -- the --
the -- the -- the shouts,

21:53.780 --> 21:57.417
the -- the name-calling, the
bullying activities that we see.

21:57.450 --> 21:58.851
I think, really,

21:58.885 --> 22:00.787
the biggest stumbling block
in our way as our country

22:00.820 --> 22:05.392
is stigma and discrimination
for persons living with HIV,

22:05.425 --> 22:06.793
but of course

22:06.826 --> 22:10.029
for our communities
that are more vulnerable.

22:10.062 --> 22:13.132
**

22:13.165 --> 22:16.002
PAGE: Thanks in part to funding
from international partners,

22:16.035 --> 22:19.739
this clinic provides
affordable treatment to anyone.

22:19.772 --> 22:21.374
But unfortunately,

22:21.408 --> 22:24.110
it must keep a very low profile
in the community.

22:24.143 --> 22:28.448
Michael is a 24-year-old
HIV-positive gay man

22:28.481 --> 22:31.017
who receives treatment here.

22:31.050 --> 22:33.520
He stopped going
to state clinics

22:33.553 --> 22:36.989
after the discrimination
he faced from health workers.

22:37.023 --> 22:40.893
He has agreed to speak with us,
with his identity hidden,

22:40.927 --> 22:43.796
at an undisclosed location.

22:43.830 --> 22:46.433
-I'm Ellen.
-Hi. I'm Ian.

22:46.466 --> 22:48.000
-Hi.
-Nice to meet you.

22:48.034 --> 22:50.036
PAGE: How are you?
Yeah?

22:50.069 --> 22:53.873
So, what is it like to have HIV
and live in Jamaica?

23:19.799 --> 23:21.501
Mm-hmm.

23:21.534 --> 23:24.971
I don't associate
with persons in my community.

23:25.004 --> 23:27.139
-Mm-hmm.
-I try to stay indoor.

23:27.173 --> 23:32.745
If I am going somewhere,
I take my bus, I take my taxi.

23:32.779 --> 23:35.715
I mean, you seem to have found
some hope in the situation.

23:35.748 --> 23:38.751
And you're getting
some sort of treatment.

23:52.198 --> 23:53.533
Mm-hmm.

23:58.605 --> 23:59.839
Right.

24:02.609 --> 24:03.576
Mm.

24:03.610 --> 24:05.612
**

24:07.847 --> 24:09.549
**

24:09.582 --> 24:12.719
PAGE: Arguably,
those hit hardest by the effects

24:12.752 --> 24:15.822
of poverty, violence,
and homophobia in Jamaica

24:15.855 --> 24:17.990
are the queer homeless youth.

24:18.024 --> 24:21.093
They are often referred to
as the gully queens

24:21.127 --> 24:22.895
because they used to squat

24:22.929 --> 24:26.533
in the gullies or storm drains
of New Kingston.

24:26.566 --> 24:29.168
They are some
of the most visible members

24:29.201 --> 24:31.604
of the local LGBTQ community
here

24:31.638 --> 24:34.507
and recently gained
international attention

24:34.541 --> 24:37.209
when one of their own,
Dwayne Jones, was killed

24:37.243 --> 24:41.581
by an angry mob after allegedly
attending a dancehall night.

24:41.614 --> 24:45.952
Since the attack, human-rights
organizations around the world

24:45.985 --> 24:49.589
have called for queer
protections under Jamaican law.

24:49.622 --> 24:53.926
But ironically, the youth have
been left even more vulnerable.

24:53.960 --> 24:55.695
For their safety,

24:55.728 --> 24:59.265
we have been asked to not film
outside their compound.

24:59.298 --> 25:03.235
[ Indistinct shouting ]

25:03.269 --> 25:06.639
[ Indistinct talking ]

25:06.673 --> 25:08.808
[ Radio playing, dog barking ]

25:08.841 --> 25:11.277
DANIEL:
How many people live here?

25:11.310 --> 25:13.245
-14?
-Yes.

25:13.279 --> 25:15.147
How long have you been here?

25:25.858 --> 25:27.694
And how does it happen?

25:27.727 --> 25:31.964
Someone just lights something on
fire, or they throw, like, a --

25:31.998 --> 25:33.265
Mm-hmm.

25:34.333 --> 25:36.002
**

25:55.287 --> 25:56.923
Mm-hmm.

26:00.727 --> 26:02.094
Right.

26:04.664 --> 26:06.298
It'd be great
if you'd share your story

26:06.332 --> 26:08.334
about, like, growing up.

26:10.637 --> 26:12.138
-Oh!
-You're running the show?

26:12.171 --> 26:13.272
Yeah.

26:14.874 --> 26:16.342
Mm-hmm.
-Oh, okay.

26:19.345 --> 26:21.113
Mm-hmm.

26:37.897 --> 26:38.998
Mm-hmm.

26:41.801 --> 26:44.937
-And people will hurt you
and yell...
-Yeah, people --

26:47.674 --> 26:48.875
Oh, my God.

26:48.908 --> 26:50.710
Someone threw acid on you?

26:51.944 --> 26:53.145
Really?

26:54.146 --> 26:55.214
-Monday?!
-Monday?!

26:55.247 --> 26:57.116
-Yeah.
-Wait, where were --

26:57.149 --> 26:58.751
Okay, wait.

26:58.785 --> 27:02.021
And just -- The bullet
went in and out, or...

27:08.427 --> 27:10.096
Right.

27:14.266 --> 27:16.135
PAGE:
What would you like to do?

27:16.168 --> 27:19.405
Sort of, what are your dreams
and your ambitions?

27:21.808 --> 27:23.976
Mm-hmm.

27:28.080 --> 27:29.381
Mm.

27:34.754 --> 27:38.024
Mm. So, what about
your personal story?

27:51.871 --> 27:53.372
Mm-hmm.

27:54.807 --> 27:57.176
Why do you think it bothers
people so much

27:57.209 --> 27:59.846
when a boy wants to wear
girl clothes?

28:11.090 --> 28:12.725
Mm.

28:13.893 --> 28:15.728
Mm.
-Mm.

28:15.762 --> 28:18.831
Are you here mostly?
Do you leave much, or...

28:22.201 --> 28:23.936
Mm.

28:27.073 --> 28:28.407
MINDY: Yes.

28:28.440 --> 28:31.010
What does a better life
look like for you?

28:34.213 --> 28:35.748
Mm-hmm.

28:41.220 --> 28:42.955
Mm-hmm.

28:42.989 --> 28:45.257
What's your relationship like
with your family?

28:55.101 --> 28:56.936
Mm-hmm.

28:59.038 --> 29:00.439
Mm.

29:08.014 --> 29:09.481
PAGE:
In Jamaica, there aren't

29:09.515 --> 29:12.084
any well-established
homeless shelters

29:12.118 --> 29:15.287
to provide long-term housing
for the queer community.

29:15.321 --> 29:19.458
Yvonne McCalla Sobers is a
prominent human-rights activist

29:19.491 --> 29:22.328
who is trying to raise money
for shelter and job training

29:22.361 --> 29:23.863
for these young people.

29:23.896 --> 29:25.397
**

29:25.431 --> 29:29.368
There's just so much anger
towards anyone who's LGBT,

29:29.401 --> 29:32.538
and I'm just wondering,
what do you think causes that?

29:32.571 --> 29:36.809
There's a culture that says,
"Normal is straight."

29:36.843 --> 29:40.446
There's also the Bible-based
organizations...

29:40.479 --> 29:42.248
-Mm-hmm.
-...which justify

29:42.281 --> 29:45.184
hate
of the LGBT community

29:45.217 --> 29:47.586
based on certain
writings in the Bible.

29:47.619 --> 29:50.356
A lot of the venom is recent.
-Mm.

29:50.389 --> 29:54.326
And it comes
from right-wing conservative,

29:54.360 --> 29:56.028
Pentecostal U.S. churches.

29:56.062 --> 29:57.496
-Mm-hmm.
-Mm.

29:57.529 --> 30:00.933
And they come here
and they preach the hate.

30:00.967 --> 30:03.335
-Mm-hmm.
-Now we're insisting

30:03.369 --> 30:06.906
on holding
onto British colonial heritage.

30:06.939 --> 30:08.407
Mm-hmm.

30:08.440 --> 30:13.079
So I'm trying to say that
there is a nuance situation.

30:13.112 --> 30:15.915
After the most strongly
homophobic people

30:15.948 --> 30:20.219
think our youth are too open
and too overt

30:20.252 --> 30:21.988
and they're not following
the rules,

30:22.021 --> 30:24.023
which are
"don't ask, don't tell..."
-Mm-hmm.

30:24.056 --> 30:26.592
...and, you know, really stay
in the closet.

30:26.625 --> 30:29.395
So they've been traumatized,
re-traumatized,

30:29.428 --> 30:32.098
and traumatized 10 times
on top of that.

30:32.131 --> 30:36.135
The same story is repeated
many times among the youth,

30:36.168 --> 30:38.004
like we have just seen.

30:38.037 --> 30:41.540
And I'm not sure how I would act
in their place.

30:41.573 --> 30:44.643
-Right. Mm-hmm.
-Yeah. Yeah. Yeah.

30:49.949 --> 30:52.551
**

30:52.584 --> 30:57.089
PAGE:
We've seen just how difficult
it is to change hearts and minds

30:57.123 --> 30:59.992
on the issue of LGBTQ acceptance
in Jamaica.

31:00.026 --> 31:02.661
But there are
some bold young activists

31:02.694 --> 31:05.965
looking to push queer rights
forward.

31:05.998 --> 31:10.402
Angeline Jackson recently
received international attention

31:10.436 --> 31:13.105
for her work in the community.

31:13.139 --> 31:15.207
-Wah gwaan, Jamaica?
[ Cheers and applause ]

31:15.241 --> 31:16.642
PAGE: Last year,

31:16.675 --> 31:19.111
during President Obama's visit
to the country,

31:19.145 --> 31:21.513
he acknowledged her work
as a young leader.

31:21.547 --> 31:23.916
Several years ago,
when Angeline was 19,

31:23.950 --> 31:26.452
she and a friend were kidnapped,
held at gunpoint,

31:26.485 --> 31:28.220
sexually assaulted.

31:28.254 --> 31:30.222
And as a woman and as a lesbian,

31:30.256 --> 31:32.558
justice and society
were not always on her side.

31:32.591 --> 31:34.260
But instead of remaining silent,

31:34.293 --> 31:37.063
she chose to speak out
and started her own organization

31:37.096 --> 31:39.431
to advocate for women like her
and get them justice.

31:39.465 --> 31:41.968
But more than anything,
she cares about her Jamaica

31:42.001 --> 31:44.536
and making it a place where
everybody, no matter their color

31:44.570 --> 31:46.572
or their class
or their sexual orientation,

31:46.605 --> 31:48.607
can live in equality
and opportunity.

31:48.640 --> 31:51.944
PAGE:
We're meeting with Angeline
to learn more about her work

31:51.978 --> 31:54.713
and her experience
being a lesbian in Jamaica.

31:54.746 --> 31:56.215
-Thanks for having us.
-Thanks, yeah.

31:56.248 --> 31:58.117
-This is your pad, huh?
-It is.

31:58.150 --> 32:01.287
Life, work, and everything
happens in this space.

32:01.320 --> 32:02.421
-All in here?
-Yeah.

32:02.454 --> 32:04.056
I feel safest at home.

32:04.090 --> 32:05.491
If I go in the streets,

32:05.524 --> 32:08.727
then I'm a little bit more
concerned about my safety.

32:08.760 --> 32:10.696
Over the last few days,

32:10.729 --> 32:14.133
we've, you know, been hearing
these stories and experiencing

32:14.166 --> 32:17.503
how hard it is just to be gay
and live your life --

32:17.536 --> 32:19.171
let alone to be
someone like you

32:19.205 --> 32:21.240
who's really, really pushing
things forward.

32:21.273 --> 32:24.443
It's like, I couldn't imagine
having that strength.

32:24.476 --> 32:26.979
In 2009, when I experienced
sexual violence,

32:27.013 --> 32:29.515
it was targeted because
of my sexual orientation.

32:29.548 --> 32:31.450
And so I, you know --
I started saying

32:31.483 --> 32:34.586
activism is the rent
I'm gonna pay for my time here.

32:34.620 --> 32:36.288
-Mm-hmm.
-And so that decision

32:36.322 --> 32:38.724
led to everything else that
has happened up to this point.

32:38.757 --> 32:40.159
Do you mind to tell us

32:40.192 --> 32:42.161
the actual story
about what did happen?

32:42.194 --> 32:44.730
Sure.
I had met a few persons

32:44.763 --> 32:47.699
on a Caribbean network
for LGBT people.

32:47.733 --> 32:50.669
And then, deciding to meet
this particular woman.

32:50.702 --> 32:53.105
You know, I always suggest
you go and meet persons,

32:53.139 --> 32:54.673
you do it in public,
carry a friend.

32:54.706 --> 32:57.309
I didn't do the public, but
I did the carry a friend part,

32:57.343 --> 32:59.645
which is what I thought,
you know, at least I was safe

32:59.678 --> 33:01.213
in that way.
-Right.

33:01.247 --> 33:02.714
We went to meet
the -- the -- the woman.

33:02.748 --> 33:05.584
We got to her community,
gave her a call,

33:05.617 --> 33:08.087
and she says she's gonna ask
her stepbrother to come for us.

33:08.120 --> 33:09.488
So her stepbrother comes.

33:09.521 --> 33:12.158
And I remember turning around
at one point

33:12.191 --> 33:15.427
and seeing this person running
along the path towards us.

33:15.461 --> 33:18.097
He has a tam on his head and
a handkerchief up to his eyes

33:18.130 --> 33:19.531
and a gun in his hand.

33:19.565 --> 33:21.800
And I stood there
and I was like, "Jesus Christ."

33:21.833 --> 33:24.070
"Okay. Life is done"
kind of thing.

33:24.103 --> 33:28.207
And so I was forced to do
oral sex on the gunman,

33:28.240 --> 33:31.377
on the stepbrother,
and on my friend.

33:31.410 --> 33:34.346
She had to do oral sex

33:34.380 --> 33:38.217
on the gunman
and on the stepbrother.

33:39.418 --> 33:44.256
And then I had to watch
as she was raped by both men.

33:46.525 --> 33:49.161
When I got home, I went into the
house and I called the police.

33:49.195 --> 33:51.597
And I said, "What do I do
if I've been raped?"

33:51.630 --> 33:54.166
-Mm.
-The first response I got
from the police was,

33:54.200 --> 33:56.335
"You should leave this lifestyle
and go back to church."

33:56.368 --> 33:58.337
And because
that was the response,

33:58.370 --> 34:00.606
my dad helped me
and we got to the police

34:00.639 --> 34:03.242
in the parish where the rape
actually happened.

34:03.275 --> 34:05.644
And that was where
the process went forward.

34:05.677 --> 34:08.380
What were the consequences
that your attacker faced?

34:08.414 --> 34:09.848
Out of 20-something years,

34:09.881 --> 34:12.251
only two to four years
for violating my body --

34:12.284 --> 34:15.154
only to realize in 2013
that the case was appealed

34:15.187 --> 34:17.289
and he was not --
he was not serving time.

34:17.323 --> 34:19.691
This person's out
on the streets. I was mad.

34:19.725 --> 34:21.693
And so I wrote a note
on Facebook,

34:21.727 --> 34:23.662
as a survivor
of sexual violence.

34:23.695 --> 34:27.433
When you shared your story,
was there any backlash?

34:27.466 --> 34:28.467
No.

34:28.500 --> 34:29.668
-No?
-Wow.

34:29.701 --> 34:31.770
It was,
"Thank you for speaking up,

34:31.803 --> 34:34.206
regardless
of your sexual orientation."

34:34.240 --> 34:36.508
That was the conversation.
-What do you see happening?

34:36.542 --> 34:38.644
Like, how do you see change
moving forward

34:38.677 --> 34:40.846
and say, potentially, like,
five-year mark?

34:40.879 --> 34:42.781
Five years,
I see us having

34:42.814 --> 34:45.184
a comprehensive
antidiscrimination legislation,

34:45.217 --> 34:46.752
something that protects
all people,

34:46.785 --> 34:49.221
regardless of sexual orientation
or gender identity.

34:49.255 --> 34:51.190
10 years, I mean,
I'd love to say marriage,

34:51.223 --> 34:53.125
but that will probably be
another 50 years.

34:53.159 --> 34:54.726
Who knows, 20?

34:54.760 --> 34:58.530
But I see us changing society --
getting persons to the point

34:58.564 --> 35:01.300
of, at the very least,
let's just respect gay people.

35:01.333 --> 35:02.601
Let's not kill them.

35:02.634 --> 35:04.436
I'm actually, too,
also interested

35:04.470 --> 35:06.472
in the work
and everything you're doing.

35:06.505 --> 35:10.376
In 2013, I started Quality
of Citizenship Jamaica, QCJ.

35:10.409 --> 35:12.678
It's about education,
research, activism.

35:12.711 --> 35:15.514
So we've done self-defense
training, because the research

35:15.547 --> 35:18.284
said that women wanted to know
how to defend themselves.

35:18.317 --> 35:21.287
And then activism for us
is silent protests.

35:21.320 --> 35:24.756
Put a rainbow flag, a Jamaica
flag in the middle of Kingston.

35:24.790 --> 35:25.791
[ Laughs ]

35:25.824 --> 35:27.826
Wow.

35:27.859 --> 35:30.762
So it's activism
in any way that we can do it.

35:30.796 --> 35:33.799
We're trying to build up
individuals within the community

35:33.832 --> 35:35.334
to be their own activist.

35:35.367 --> 35:38.404
So they may not be doing
a Vice TV interview,

35:38.437 --> 35:39.705
but they may do a small talk

35:39.738 --> 35:41.507
with somebody
on the street corner

35:41.540 --> 35:44.410
who they can then impact, who
then impacts five other people

35:44.443 --> 35:47.613
because that's how
we have to do activism
in our different ways.

35:47.646 --> 35:49.881
But I think we've made
a lot of noise

35:49.915 --> 35:52.851
for an organization with five
full-time volunteer employees.

35:52.884 --> 35:54.386
-Wow.
-Oh.

35:54.420 --> 35:55.954
And I'm beyond existing.

35:55.987 --> 35:59.558
I'm ready to live in Jamaica,
because it is my Jamaica, too.

35:59.591 --> 36:01.960
-Yeah, that's pretty amazing.
-It's a big deal. Yeah.

36:01.993 --> 36:03.495
So, thank you.
-Thank you.

36:03.529 --> 36:05.197
Thank you so much.

